"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":[{\"tool_use_id\":\"toolu_013zSf8MjDXHQn1j7aYkDKfw\",\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"content\":\"     1→# Attribution\\n     2→\\n     3→## Overview\\n     4→\\n     5→Attribution tracks how much of a commit came from the agent vs the user. When a user commits code after working with an AI agent, the CLI calculates what percentage of the changes were agent-written vs human-written.\\n     6→\\n     7→This is captured in the `Entire-Attribution` trailer on commits:\\n     8→\\n     9→```\\n    10→feat: Add user authentication\\n    11→\\n    12→Entire-Checkpoint: a3b2c4d5e6f7\\n    13→Entire-Attribution: 73% agent (146/200 lines)\\n    14→```\\n    15→\\n    16→## The Challenge\\n    17→\\n    18→Attribution seems simple: diff the base commit against the final commit and count who wrote what. But there's a fundamental challenge: **the agent and user interleave their work**.\\n    19→\\n    20→A typical session looks like:\\n    21→\\n    22→1. User writes some code\\n    23→2. Agent runs, adds more code (checkpoint 1)\\n    24→3. User edits the agent's code and adds their own\\n    25→4. Agent runs again (checkpoint 2)\\n    26→5. User makes final tweaks\\n    27→6. User commits\\n    28→\\n    29→The checkpoint snapshots capture the worktree state at each moment, but that state includes *both* agent work and user edits made since the last checkpoint. We need to untangle these contributions.\\n    30→\\n    31→## Architecture\\n    32→\\n    33→### Data Collection\\n    34→\\n    35→Attribution data is collected at two points:\\n    36→\\n    37→**1. At prompt start** (`CalculatePromptAttribution`)\\n    38→\\n    39→Before each agent run, we capture what the user changed since the last checkpoint:\\n    40→- `UserLinesAdded` / `UserLinesRemoved` - aggregate counts\\n    41→- `UserAddedPerFile` - per-file breakdown of user additions\\n    42→\\n    43→This happens *before* the agent runs, so we can cleanly separate \\\"user edits between prompts\\\" from \\\"agent work during prompt\\\".\\n    44→\\n    45→**2. At commit time** (`CalculateAttributionWithAccumulated`)\\n    46→\\n    47→When the user commits, we calculate final attribution by:\\n    48→1. Summing accumulated user edits from all `PromptAttribution` records\\n    49→2. Adding post-checkpoint user edits (shadow → head diff)\\n    50→3. Calculating agent work (base → shadow minus accumulated user edits)\\n    51→4. Computing the final percentage\\n    52→\\n    53→### Key Files\\n    54→\\n    55→- `manual_commit_attribution.go` - Core attribution calculation logic\\n    56→- `manual_commit_types.go` - `PromptAttribution` struct definition\\n    57→- `manual_commit_hooks.go` - Hook that triggers attribution calculation on commit\\n    58→\\n    59→## Line Ownership Tracking\\n    60→\\n    61→When a user modifies code, we need to know: did they modify agent lines or their own lines?\\n    62→\\n    63→**Example problem:**\\n    64→1. Agent adds 10 lines\\n    65→2. User adds 5 lines of their own\\n    66→3. User removes 3 lines and adds 3 different lines (a modification)\\n    67→\\n    68→If those 3 removed lines were the user's own code, agent attribution should be unaffected. If they were agent lines, agent attribution should decrease.\\n    69→\\n    70→### Approaches Considered\\n    71→\\n    72→#### Git Blame Against Checkpoints\\n    73→\\n    74→Use git's blame to trace line ownership through checkpoint commits.\\n    75→\\n    76→```go\\n    77→// Lines introduced in shadow commits = agent lines\\n    78→func getLineOwnership(repo *git.Repository, baseCommit, shadowCommit plumbing.Hash, filePath string) (agentLines, userLines []int) {\\n    79→    // git blame --porcelain <shadow-commit> -- <file>\\n    80→}\\n    81→```\\n    82→\\n    83→| Aspect | Assessment |\\n    84→|--------|------------|\\n    85→| Accuracy | High |\\n    86→| Complexity | High - requires shelling to git CLI |\\n    87→| Performance | Expensive at attribution time |\\n    88→\\n    89→#### Line Hash Tracking\\n    90→\\n    91→Track ownership via content hashes of individual lines.\\n    92→\\n    93→```go\\n    94→type LineOwnership struct {\\n    95→    AgentLineHashes map[string]bool  // SHA256 of line content\\n    96→}\\n    97→```\\n    98→\\n    99→| Aspect | Assessment |\\n   100→|--------|------------|\\n   101→| Accuracy | Low |\\n   102→| Complexity | Medium |\\n   103→| Performance | Fast lookups |\\n   104→\\n   105→**Fatal flaw:** Common lines like `}`, `return nil`, and blank lines have identical hashes. When a user removes a `}`, we can't determine which one (agent's or user's) was removed.\\n   106→\\n   107→#### Position-Aware Diff Tracking\\n   108→\\n   109→Track line ownership by file position, updating ranges as edits happen.\\n   110→\\n   111→```go\\n   112→type FileOwnership struct {\\n   113→    AgentRanges []LineRange  // e.g., [{Start: 5, End: 15}]\\n   114→}\\n   115→```\\n   116→\\n   117→| Aspect | Assessment |\\n   118→|--------|------------|\\n   119→| Accuracy | High |\\n   120→| Complexity | Very High - complex range arithmetic |\\n   121→| Performance | Must process every diff sequentially |\\n   122→\\n   123→#### Per-File Pool Heuristic (Selected)\\n   124→\\n   125→Track aggregate ownership counts per file. Use LIFO assumption: users modify their own recent additions before touching agent code.\\n   126→\\n   127→```go\\n   128→// PromptAttribution includes per-file tracking\\n   129→type PromptAttribution struct {\\n   130→    UserLinesAdded   int\\n   131→    UserLinesRemoved int\\n   132→    UserAddedPerFile map[string]int  // Per-file breakdown\\n   133→}\\n   134→\\n   135→// When user removes lines, assume they remove their own first\\n   136→func estimateUserSelfModifications(\\n   137→    accumulatedUserAddedPerFile map[string]int,\\n   138→    postCheckpointUserRemovedPerFile map[string]int,\\n   139→) int {\\n   140→    var selfModified int\\n   141→    for filePath, removed := range postCheckpointUserRemovedPerFile {\\n   142→        userAddedToFile := accumulatedUserAddedPerFile[filePath]\\n   143→        selfModified += min(removed, userAddedToFile)\\n   144→    }\\n   145→    return selfModified\\n   146→}\\n   147→```\\n   148→\\n   149→| Aspect | Assessment |\\n   150→|--------|------------|\\n   151→| Accuracy | Medium - good for common case |\\n   152→| Complexity | Low |\\n   153→| Performance | Fast |\\n   154→\\n   155→### Why Per-File Pools\\n   156→\\n   157→1. **Solves the common case**: When users modify their own recent code (the typical pattern), attribution remains accurate\\n   158→\\n   159→2. **Sidesteps line identity problems**: We don't need to solve \\\"which `}` was removed\\\" - we reason at the file level\\n   160→\\n   161→3. **Reasonable assumption**: \\\"Users modify their own recent code before agent code\\\" matches typical editing patterns\\n   162→\\n   163→4. **Low implementation cost**: Just adds a map to `PromptAttribution`\\n   164→\\n   165→### Trade-offs Accepted\\n   166→\\n   167→- **Imprecise for adversarial cases**: If a user deliberately removes agent code while keeping their own, attribution will be slightly off\\n   168→- **File-level granularity**: We can't distinguish modifications within different functions of the same file\\n   169→\\n   170→These are acceptable because:\\n   171→- Attribution is informational, not security-critical\\n   172→- Users have no incentive to game attribution\\n   173→- Perfect accuracy would require reimplementing git-blame\\n   174→\\n   175→## Calculation Flow\\n   176→\\n   177→```\\n   178→Session Start (base commit)\\n   179→    │\\n   180→    ▼\\n   181→┌─────────────────────────────────┐\\n   182→│ User edits files                │\\n   183→└─────────────────────────────────┘\\n   184→    │\\n   185→    ▼\\n   186→┌─────────────────────────────────┐\\n   187→│ Prompt submitted                │\\n   188→│ → CalculatePromptAttribution()  │\\n   189→│ → Capture user edits per file   │\\n   190→└─────────────────────────────────┘\\n   191→    │\\n   192→    ▼\\n   193→┌─────────────────────────────────┐\\n   194→│ Agent runs, creates checkpoint  │\\n   195→│ → Shadow branch updated         │\\n   196→└─────────────────────────────────┘\\n   197→    │\\n   198→    ▼\\n   199→    ... (repeat for multiple prompts) ...\\n   200→    │\\n   201→    ▼\\n   202→┌─────────────────────────────────┐\\n   203→│ User makes final edits          │\\n   204→└─────────────────────────────────┘\\n   205→    │\\n   206→    ▼\\n   207→┌─────────────────────────────────┐\\n   208→│ User commits                    │\\n   209→│ → CalculateAttributionWith-     │\\n   210→│   Accumulated()                 │\\n   211→│ → Sum all PromptAttributions    │\\n   212→│ → Add post-checkpoint edits     │\\n   213→│ → Estimate self-modifications   │\\n   214→│ → Calculate final percentage    │\\n   215→└─────────────────────────────────┘\\n   216→    │\\n   217→    ▼\\n   218→Commit with Entire-Attribution trailer\\n   219→```\\n   220→\\n   221→## Example Calculation\\n   222→\\n   223→**Scenario:**\\n   224→- Agent adds 10 lines to `main.go`\\n   225→- User adds 5 lines to `main.go` (between checkpoints)\\n   226→- User modifies 3 of their own lines (removes 3, adds 3 different)\\n   227→\\n   228→**Calculation:**\\n   229→```\\n   230→base → shadow: 15 lines added (10 agent + 5 user in snapshot)\\n   231→accumulatedUserAdded: 5 (from PromptAttribution)\\n   232→totalAgentAdded: 15 - 5 = 10\\n   233→\\n   234→shadow → head: +3 added, -3 removed (user's modification)\\n   235→postCheckpointUserAdded: 3\\n   236→postCheckpointUserRemoved: 3\\n   237→\\n   238→totalUserAdded: 5 + 3 = 8\\n   239→totalUserRemoved: 3\\n   240→totalHumanModified: min(8, 3) = 3\\n   241→\\n   242→// Per-file tracking kicks in:\\n   243→userSelfModified: min(3 removed from main.go, 5 user added to main.go) = 3\\n   244→humanModifiedAgent: 3 - 3 = 0  // No agent lines were modified!\\n   245→\\n   246→agentLinesInCommit: 10 - 0 = 10  // Agent attribution preserved\\n   247→totalCommitted: 10 + 5 = 15\\n   248→agentPercentage: 10/15 = 66.7%\\n   249→```\\n   250→\\n   251→Without per-file tracking, we would have incorrectly subtracted 3 from agent lines, giving 46.7% instead of 66.7%.\\n   252→\\n   253→## References\\n   254→\\n   255→- Implementation: `cmd/entire/cli/strategy/manual_commit_attribution.go`\\n   256→- Types: `cmd/entire/cli/strategy/manual_commit_types.go`\\n   257→- Tests: `cmd/entire/cli/strategy/manual_commit_attribution_test.go`\\n   258→\"}]},\"uuid\":\"a9bce378-e2b2-452d-aa20-80833b23e780\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-06T17:44:52.288Z\"},\"type\":\"agent_progress\",\"prompt\":\"\",\"agentId\":\"afc698f953c341c14\"},\"toolUseID\":\"agent_msg_01KLfjXamBrHzDU5JPCL1LET\",\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_012SQ2zcCKKv5nU63NZZr8r5\",\"uuid\":\"d7e5a30f-40a4-499d-a2fd-54ff259e14db\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-06T17:44:52.719Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"d7e5a30f-40a4-499d-a2fd-54ff259e14db\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/alisha/Projects/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"09356618-966a-4751-9a19-8254300ef35a\",\"version\":\"2.1.70\",\"gitBranch\":\"main\",\"slug\":\"linked-chasing-storm\",\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"message\":{\"type\":\"assistant\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-06T17:44:52.930Z\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001\",\"id\":\"msg_01VuS4pdAdDcLQnyRrw9kzrv\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"tool_use\",\"id\":\"toolu_01SBs3HQuKYkxETSejGUhpHE\",\"name\":\"Read\",\"input\":{\"file_path\":\"/Users/alisha/Projects/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/session/state.go\",\"offset\":150,\"limit\":100},\"caller\":{\"type\":\"direct\"}}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":7,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":2942,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":79667,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":2942,\"ephemeral_1h_